-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This evidence is subm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">itted by RCUK and represents its independent views.  It does not include, or necessarily reflect the views of the Knowledge and Innovation Group in the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS).  The submission is made on behalf of the following</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Councils:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council (EPSRC)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Natural Environment Research Council (NERC)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Biotechnology and Biological Sciences Research Council (BBSRC)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Science and Technology Facilities Council (STFC)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Q1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt">What types of CCS </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt">technology are currently being developed and how do they differ from one another?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The EPSRC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and NERC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, as part of the RCUK Energy Programme, support a breadth of research in the field of carbon capture and storage. The portfolio in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cludes, but is not limite</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d to: capture technologies, pre- and post- combustion capture, oxyfuel methods, chemical l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ooping, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">retrofit, p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ower plant efficiencies and scale up, pipeline engineering for transport, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">geological storage, including injection </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and monitoring methods.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Four new projects were funded</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by ESPRC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in April 2013 totalling £3.27 million in the area of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> injection </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and monitoring in the geological storage challenges area, including</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Injection and Storage Short and long-term behaviour at different spatial scales”, “Fingerprinting captured CO2 using natural tracers: Determining CO2 fate and proving ownership”, “DiSECCS: Diagnostic Seismic toolbox for the Efficient Control of CO2 Storag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e” and “The impaCt of hydrOcarbon depletioN on the Treatment of cAprocks within performance assessment for CO2 InjectioN schemes – CONTAIN”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Further information and details of these research consortia can be found on the Grants on the Web portal.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As well</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as “conventional” approaches to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">carbon capture</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (which are primarily covered by the remit of EPSRC)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> increasing the root biomass of crops, at depth</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, may help to sequester carbon in agricultural soils (which are typically carbon-poor compared with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">non-cultivated soils), where it could be held it long-term stora</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ge. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">his could make a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">significant contribution</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to mitigating greenhouse gas emissions from agriculture (which represent 8% of the UK’s total greenhouse gas emissions</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Under the auspices </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of the UK Global Food Security Programme, BBSRC and NERC are supporting a £4.5M soils research programme</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to investigate how agri-ecosystems respond to changes in management or the environment.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The programme aims to inform the development of innovations t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hat will improve the sustainability and productivity of agriculture, and increase resilience to environmental change. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Facilities for which STFC has responsibility are regularly used for CCS related research. The work is often performed in conjunction </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">funding from other research councils and examples include the characterisation (at the ISIS neutron source) of porous solids such as ‘NOTT-300’ which are being developed to provide green, cost-effective carbon capture solutions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Another example is a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">roject to develop a novel and more cost effective technique for the continuous monitoring of future CCS sites for carbon dioxide (CO2) by using cosmic rays.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Geoscientists, particle physicists and engineers will examine the potential of using muons -sub-at</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">omic particles from cosmic rays- which cascade from the upper atmosphere and go on to penetrate rock several kilometres underground. The detection of cosmic ray muons can be used to map the density profile of the material above the detectors and hence meas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ure on-going levels of CO2 in any potential carbon store.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The team comprises STFC Rutherford Appleton Laboratory, Durham University, Newcastle University, the Universities of Sheffield and Bath, and NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory, Caltech supported by Prem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ier Oil &amp; Gas and Cleveland Potash Limited.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Department of Energy and Climate Change (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DECC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is providing £647,000 for the monitoring project alongside matched funding from industry and the devices developed will be tested deep underground at the STFC resea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rch laboratory at the Boulby mine.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; margin:5pt 0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Q2 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt">What contribution could CCS make towards the UK’s decarbonisation targets? Are the UK Government’s expectations reasonable in this regard?</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The RCUK Energy Programme funds a balanced spectrum of low carbon innovation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">technologies which encompasses wind, marine, nuclear, solar, bioenergy, energy storage, power networks, hydrogen and fuel cells, and aspects of end use energy demand, of which 7.8% of the entire energy portfolio funding contributes to the underpinning CCS </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">research and 11.2% includes CCS and related oil, gas, combustion and conventional energy generation.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">All of these contribute to the UK’s decarbonisation targets.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With twice as much carbon stored in soils as is present in the atmosphere, and a significant p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">roportion of the world’s soils under cultivated land, even small gains in carbon storage in agricultural soils (paragraph 5 above) might contribute significantly to the mitigation of dangerous global greenhouse gas levels. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One model</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> suggests that a breed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing strategy to increase the root biomass of crops could potentially have a substantial effect in helping to stabilize atmospheric CO2.</span></li></ol><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; margin:5pt 0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Q3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt">Are there any potential benefits (e.g. the ability to export CCS technology abroad) of successfully developing CCS to the UK economy and, if so, what are they?     </span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 5pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The RCUK Energy Programme acknowledges the importance of transnational collaboration to ben</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eficial growth for the UK economy. The CCS research programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> through EPSRC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has recently established research ventures with countries in Europe (Norway, Poland and Greece) through the FENCO-NET, where collaborative grant out-comes will be announced by the end of 2013. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 5pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">EPSRC facilitates </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CCS collaborations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which are now</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> well estab</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lished with Chinese partners, and a number of joint funded projects are underway, aiming to facilitate growth and increased technolo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gy readiness of CCS methods</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in the two respective countries.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 5pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is also on-going collaboration with Japanese researchers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on the NERC funded, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Plymouth Marine Laboratory</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> led, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">project Quantifying and Monitoring Potential Ecosystem Impacts of Geological Carbon Storage (QICS)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (see question 5 below for details).  This research has also been presented in the US.</span></li></ol><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; margin:5pt 0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Q4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt">What are the mai</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt">n barriers (e.g. economic, political, regulatory, scientific and social) to developing large-scale integrated CCS projects in the UK and internationally? How can they be overcome?</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These research topics are covered by the academic communities who hold resea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rch grants awarded through the research councils. The outcomes of their research are therefore used to help inform experts of these aspects of CCS. It is actively encouraged in the research councils managed calls to include work on these issues to ensure t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hat safely, policy and public acceptance are addressed in the context of the research being completed.</span></li></ol><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; margin:5pt 0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Q5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt"> Are there any safety issues associated with capturing, transporting and storing carbon dioxide? How could they be overcome? Who should have responsibility for ensuring these activities are safe?</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is the intention of the cross-council energy programme to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ensure that not only a balanced portfolio of low carbon innovation technologies are funded (not exclusively CCS), but also that cross discipline research is completed by co-funding between the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">research councils. In this capacity, it is envisaged that safe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ty issues are addressed in the remit of these research proposals.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For example, the NERC funded project Quantifying and Monitoring Potential Ecosystem Impacts of Geological Carbon Storage (QICS)</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, led by Plymouth Marine Laboratory in collaboration with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">British Geological Survey, National Oceanography Centre and the Scottish Association for Marine Science involved a world-first experiment over the course of summer 2012 to monitor what might happen if CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> leaks from a sub-seabed storage reservoir into the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">marine environment.  Results from this experiment are due to be published in the near future.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The National Oceanography Centre, the British Geological Survey, and Plymouth Marine Laboratory are also involved in the ECO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> project - a collaborative project f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">unded under the European Commission's Framework Seven Programme Topic OCEAN.2010.3. The project will establish a framework of best environmental practices to guide the management of offshore CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> injection and storage and as addendum to the EU directive on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">"Geological Storage of CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">" for the marine realm. This includes the quantitative assessment of potential and actual impacts on marine ecosystems at a CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> injection facility and the entire storage site. An integral part of the project is to transfer knowled</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ge into a risk management concept and an economic valuing of the costs of leakage, monitoring, mitigation measures, and a clear communication framework. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Further, projects funded under the recent “EPSRC Challenges in Geological Storage for CCS” initiative</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> aim to look at monitoring techniques using various seismic and labelling methods, along with studies on the integrity of the caprock. Results and developments from these projects will further inform the bigger picture of safety and monitoring in the geolo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gical storage aspects of the CCS theme.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he NERC supported National Centre for Atmospheric Science</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (NCAS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> note</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ubstantial research has already been undertaken to establish the long-term stability of storage of CO2 underground, clearly a key </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">component of the safety case for CCS.  An aspect of the CCS process that is currently poorly understood, however, is the safety and environmental implications of the initial capture stage itself.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Post-combustion capture of CO2, retrofitted to existing powe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r plants, is one of the more technologically straightforward means to enable CCS in the short to medium-term.  The majority of active pilot plants are post-combustion capture CCS.  Trials in many locations have used chemical capture through the reversible </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reaction of CO2 with organic amines to produce a purified stream of CO2 from flue gas for subsequent storage. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A large uncertainty associated with th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e capture process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is the co-release of organic nitrogen by-products from the capture technology.  In mass t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">erms the by-product releases appear low.  However many of the species released, for example nitrosamines, nitramines, amides, aldehydes, imidazoles, oxazolidones, and ammonia have notable chemical toxicity.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The fate of by-product emissions from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">post-combustion capture CCS are largely unknown at present, although based on their physicochemical properties, regional scale transport in the atmosphere as gases and particles appears possible.  Internationally and nationally, R&amp;D is continuing into chem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ical engineering approaches using novel amines for CO2 capture.  It is essential that this research activity is fully joined up with research into the fate and impacts of potential by-products to ensure that CCS in the UK, from the outset, effectively bala</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nces operational and economic efficiency with suitable levels of environmental and public health protection.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Results from these studies will be used to address CCS safety issues.</span></li></ol><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Q6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt">How have other countries incentivised CCS development? How successful have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt"> they been? How do they compare to the UK’s efforts?</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">No Response</span></li></ol><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; margin:5pt 0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Q7 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt">Is the UK Government’s approach, set out in its CCS Roadmap, likely to incentivise development of CCS in the UK?</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">No Response</span></li></ol><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; margin:5pt 0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Q8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt">Could the successful development of CCS improve international efforts to mitigate climate change? What role could UK CCS play in this?  </span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In 2012, the RCUK energy programme invested £10.2 million into the establishment of a virtual research hub for CCS acti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vities – UKCCSRC</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This centre was set-up in order to coordinate: networking, data archiving, flexible small scale scoping projects and increase the visibility of the UK research areas in the CCS field. It is hoped that this united and coordinated strategy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will improve the international links with the global research scene which could reinforce international efforts for climate change mitigation.</span></li></ol><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; margin:5pt 0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Q9 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt">What are the consequences of failing to develop CCS and what alternatives are available for decarbonisation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt">if CCS fails?</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">No Response</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">August 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="